    <observation> If we recall from the previous section we learned about how to find the derivative of functions using the limit definition of a derivative.  From the activities we see that this gets cumbursome when the functions are more complicated.  In this section we will discuss a more convenient way to to calculate derivatives.</observation>
    
  <activity xml:id="activity-derivative-elementary1">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        In this activity we will try to deduce what the derivative of a power function.  Note, a power function is one in which the function is of the form <m>f(x) = x^{n}</m> where <m>n = 1, 2, 3,...</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
      <task>
      <statement> <p>Using the limit defintion of a function what is <m>f'(x)</m> for the power function <m>f(x) = x</m>? </p>
          <ol label="A">
                <li><p>-1</p></li>
                <li><p>1</p></li>
                <li><p>0</p></li>
                <li><p>Does not exist</p></li>
            </ol>
      </statement>
      </task>
      
      <task>
          <statement>
          <p> Using the limit defintion of a function what is <m>f'(x)</m> for the power function <m>f(x) = x^{2}</m>?</p>
              <ol label="A">
                <li><p>0</p></li>
                <li><p><m>-2x</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>2x</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>2x+1</m> </p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
      </task>
      
      <task>
          <statement>
          <p> Using the limit defintion of a function what is <m>f'(x)</m> for the power function <m>f(x) = x^{3}</m>?</p>
              <ol label="A">
                <li><p><m>3x^2</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>-3x^2</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>3x^2-3x</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>-3x^2+3x</m></p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
      </task>
      
      <task>
          <statement>
          <p> WITHOUT using the limit defintion of a function what is <m>f'(x)</m> for the power function <m>f(x) = x^{4}</m>? (See if you can find a pattern from the first three tasks of this activity.)</p>
              <ol label="A">
                <li><p><m>3x^2</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>3x^3</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>4x^2</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>4x^3</m></p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
      </task>
  </activity>
<definition xml:id="def-powerlaw-derivative">
       <p> The derivative of the function<m>f(x) = x^n</m>, for any nonzero real number <m>n</m>is
</p>
        <me>f'(x) = nx^{n-1}.</me>
    </definition>
    <observation>
    So far we have been using <m>f'(x)</m> or <m>f</m> prime to denote a derivative of the function <m>f(x)</m>.  However there are other ways to denote the derivative of a function.  Besides <m>f'(x)</m> there is also <m>\frac{df}{dx}</m> or dee-f dee-x.  Both notations can be used interchangabley.  If you want to take the derivative of <m>f'(x)</m> or <m>\frac{df}{dx}</m>, the notation is <m>f''(x)</m> or <m>\frac{d^2f}{dx^2}</m>; this is known as second derivative of <m>f(x)</m>.
    </observation>
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-derivative-elementary2">
    <statement>
            <p>Using <xref ref = "def-powerlaw-derivative" />, which of the following statement(s) are true?  For those statements that are wrong, correct </p>
            <ol label="A">
                <li>The derivative of <m>y = x^{10}</m> is <m>y' = 10x^{11}.</m></li>
                <li>The derivative of <m>y = x^{-8}</m> is <m>y' = -8x^{-9}.</m></li>
                <li>The derivative of <m>y = x^{100}</m> is <m>y' = 100x^{99}.</m></li>
                <li>The derivative of <m>y = x^{-17}</m> is <m>y' = -17x^{-16}.</m>.</li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <definition>
    <p>If <m>f(x) = c</m>, for some constant <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m>, then <m>f'(x) = 0</m>.
        </p>
    </definition>
    <definition>
    <p>The Constant Multiple Rule: If <m>c</m> is a constant and <m>f(x)</m> is a differentiable function, then
        <me>\frac{d}{dx}\left[cf(x)\right] = c\frac{d}{dx}\left[f(x)\right]</me>
        </p>
    </definition>
    <definition>
    <p>The Sum(Difference) Rule: If <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> are both differentiable, then
        <me>\frac{d}{dx}\left[f(x) \pm g(x)\right] = \frac{d}{dx}\left[f(x)\right]\pm\frac{d}{dx}\left[g(x)\right]</me>
        </p>
    </definition>
    <observation>
    The above definitions will be explored in the following activities
    </observation>
